our portfolio, investment thesis, and thoughts on the market.=C2=A0
Since this was the first update (and because I=E2=80=99m physically incapab=
le of writing short emails), I went in-depth on the portfolio, how the Not =
Boring Flywheel that I=E2=80=99d pitched in the Memo is working, and how I=
=E2=80=99m approaching portfolio construction. A few highlights:=C2=A0
Not Boring Capital is deploying faster than anticipated. As long as the opp=
ortunities we see continue to be strong, I=E2=80=99m going to lean into tha=
t on this and future funds. I wrote:=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m increasingly convinced that the right way for Not Boring Capita=
l to differentiate and generate strong returns is to keep fund sizes small =
and flex on deployment speed. Instead of raising a $50 million fund and try=
ing to compete to lead or to take a large percentage of the allocation in a=
 round in order for it to be meaningful, we can deploy $7-10 million funds =
every 9-12 months, and follow-on via SPVs and future funds. To the extent t=
hat the pace of good deals slows, we will slow down as well. As it stands, =
we=E2=80=99re seeing a lot of great companies and I expect to continue to d=
eploy aggressively.
Our stage mix leans slightly earlier than planned. I wrote in the Memo that=
 I was aiming to invest =E2=85=93 in Pre-Seed and Seed, =E2=85=93 in Series=
 A, and =E2=85=93 in Series B and beyond. We=E2=80=99re leaning a little bi=
t earlier, with 79% of invested dollars in Pre-Seed through Series A and 21=
% invested in Series B and beyond.
Fintech is our leading vertical. From a vertical perspective, the winner bo=
th by number of investments (6) and dollars invested ($525k) is fintech, wi=
th a focus on investing tech (Composer, Party Round, Embedded, Stonks). Her=
e=E2=80=99s the rough breakdown by vertical:=C2=A0
